nd","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bodcastle, Cornouaille,Angleterre":"Cornwall, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1100–before 1149":"about 1100–before 1149","1070–Female":"1070–Deceased","1089–1136":"1089–1136","1100–1149":"1100–1149","–1141":"–1141","1119–1175":"1119–1175","1135–1209":"1135–1209","1146–1220":"1146–1220","1054–1122":"1054–1122","before 1149":"before 1149","1220":"1220","1054":"1054","1175":"1175","1141":"1141","1070":"1070","1106":"1106","1149":"1149","Abt 1135":"about 1135","1136":"1136","1146":"1146","1135":"1135","Abt 1100":"about 1100","1134":"1134","1122":"1122","1100":"1100","1089":"1089","after January 1122":"after January 1122","1209":"1209","1119":"1119","England":"England, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Alcester, Warwickshire, England":"Alcester, Warwickshire, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Bodcastle, Cornouaille,Angleterre":"Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Corbet","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Corbett  .","History: Walter Corbet, a royal knight in 12th-century Scotland, was the first of that name in that kingdom. His 13th-century descendants were major landholders in the Borders, and in the 14th century they acquired lands in the North of Scotland."],"variants":[{"name":"Corbett","meanings":["English (West Midlands, of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>corbet</i> ‘raven’, probably denoting someone with dark hair or a dark complexion.","History: This is the name of a family descended from Hugh <i>Corbet</i>, a Norman baron who settled in Shropshire following the Norman Conquest. One of his descendants, Sir Richard Corbet, was granted land near Shrewsbury in 1223; since the 13th century, this place has been known as Moreton Corbet. The name was taken from Shropshire to Scotland in the 12th century and to northern Ireland in the 17th century, and thence to North America by at least one group of bearers of the name."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":6,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Corbet was born about 1100, in Alcester, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Robert Corbet. She married William De Bottreaux in 1134, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died before 1149, in Warwickshire, England."},"et":{"Abt 1100–before 1149":"umbes 1100–enne 1149","1070–Female":"1070–Surnud","1089–1136":"1089–1136","1100–1149":"1100–1149","–1141":"–1141","1119–1175":"1119–1175","1135–1209":"1135–1209","1146–1220":"1146–1220","1054–1122":"1054–1122","before 1149":"enne 1149","1220":"1220","1054":"1054","1175":"1175","1141":"1141","1070":"1070","1106":"1106","1149":"1149","Abt 1135":"umbes 1135","1136":"1136","1146":"1146","11